      <![CDATA[<p>Recently, Xiaomi unveiled their first flip foldable phone, <a href="https://mi.com/global/discover/article?id=3464" title="" target="_blank">the MIX Flip</a>. However, the most attention at the launch event was not on the phone itself, but on its accompanying portable photography kit. Once connected with the kit, the phone transforms into a Polaroid camera and supports AR video photo, allowing users to attach a related video to the photo they take.</p><div class="video-container"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/ZmRQSLzWgeo" frameborder="0" loading="lazy" allowfullscreen></iframe></div><p>I tried to implement a simple AR Photo using Python with numpy and OpenCV. The code can be found on <a href="https://github.com/douquan56/AR-Photo/tree/master" title="" target="_blank">Github</a>. The whole process can be divided into:</p><ol><li>Target recognition with <a href="https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/dc/dc3/tutorial_py_matcher.html" title="" target="_blank">FLANN based Matcher and SIFT Descriptors</a>.</li><li>Find perspective transformation.</li><li>Project and overlay video on the target.</li></ol><img src="/images/ar-photo-demo.gif" class="" title="Cute Steve" alt="Cute Steve">]]>
    </content>
